    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-06-02T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-06-02T04:00:00-05:00" n="884"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d884">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.003/6–249: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Peiping</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clubb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-06-02T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 2, 1949—5 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 3—1:26 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>925. ReDeptel 300, May 17.<note n="77" xml:id="d884fn77">See footnote 68, <ref
                            target="#pg_940">p. 940</ref>.</note> Presented May 29 to Chang
                    Tsung-ping (see Contel 912, May 31<note n="75" xml:id="d884fn75">Not
                        printed.</note>) memo based on Depreftel setting <pb facs="0955" n="945"
                        xml:id="pg_945"/> forth position re GATT as instructed, for presentation to
                    Minister Industry and Commerce.</p>
                <p>Chang informed me today he did not present memo or detailed contents to Yao<note
                        n="78" xml:id="d884fn78">Yao I-lin, Communist official at Peiping.</note>
                    but discussed matter in general terms by phone and was informed Communists had
                    abrogated GATT tariff because agreement was one of treaties signed by Kmt<note
                        n="79" xml:id="d884fn79">Kuomintang (Nationalist Party).</note> government,
                    that matter could perhaps be given consideration again at such time Communist
                    government recognized.</p>
                <p>Chang Tung-sun present at today’s conversation re subject.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 925; repeated Nanking 605, OffEmb Canton 141, Shanghai 615,
                    Tientsin 55.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clubb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
